---
description: Enforces consistent, strict TypeScript typing across all .ts and .tsx files. Prevents implicit any, enforces return types, and requires explicit interfaces over inline types.
globs: ["**/*.ts", "**/*.tsx"]
alwaysApply: false
---

# TypeScript Strict Typing Standards

## No Implicit `any`

Every variable, parameter, and return value must have an explicit type. Never rely on implicit `any`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function process(data) {
  return data.map(item => item.name);
}

// ✅ GOOD
function process(data: UserRecord[]): string[] {
  return data.map((item) => item.name);
}
```

## Prefer `interface` Over `type` for Object Shapes

Use `interface` for object shapes and public API contracts. Reserve `type` for unions, intersections, mapped types, and primitives.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — type alias for a plain object shape
type UserProps = {
  name: string;
  email: string;
};

// ✅ GOOD
interface UserProps {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

// ✅ GOOD — type for union/intersection
type Result = Success | Failure;
type Nullable<T> = T | null;
```

## Explicit Function Return Types

All exported functions and all functions longer than a single expression must declare their return type.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
export function getUser(id: string) {
  return db.users.findOne({ id });
}

// ✅ GOOD
export function getUser(id: string): Promise<User | null> {
  return db.users.findOne({ id });
}
```

## No `as` Type Assertions Unless Narrowing From `unknown`

Avoid `as` casts — they silence the compiler. Use type guards or runtime checks instead.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const user = response.data as User;

// ✅ GOOD
function isUser(data: unknown): data is User {
  return typeof data === "object" && data !== null && "id" in data;
}

if (isUser(response.data)) {
  const user = response.data;
}
```

## Enums: Prefer `const` Enums or String Unions

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — numeric enum (opaque at runtime)
enum Status { Active, Inactive }

// ✅ GOOD
type Status = "active" | "inactive";

// ✅ ALSO GOOD — when you need runtime object
const Status = { Active: "active", Inactive: "inactive" } as const;
type Status = (typeof Status)[keyof typeof Status];
```

## Strict Null Handling

Never use non-null assertion (`!`) to bypass null checks. Handle null/undefined explicitly.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const name = user!.name;

// ✅ GOOD
const name = user?.name ?? "Anonymous";
```

## Generic Constraints

Always constrain generic parameters when possible.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function merge<T, U>(a: T, b: U) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD
function merge<T extends Record<string, unknown>, U extends Record<string, unknown>>(
  a: T, b: U
): T & U { ... }
```
